<li id="cite_note-17"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17" title="">^</a></b> For instance, from the <a href="/wiki/Pali_Canon" title="Pali Canon" class="mw-redirect">Pali Canon</a>, see <a href="/wiki/Majjhima_Nikaya" title="Majjhima Nikaya">MN</a> 44 <a href="http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/mn/mn.044.than.html" class="external text" title="http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/mn/mn.044.than.html" rel="nofollow">(Thanissaro, 1998a)</a> and <a href="/wiki/Anguttara_Nikaya" title="Anguttara Nikaya">AN</a> 3:88 <a href="http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/an/an03/an03.088.than.html" class="external text" title="http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/an/an03/an03.088.than.html" rel="nofollow">(Thanissaro, 1998b).</a> In Mahayana tradition, the <a href="/wiki/Lotus_Sutra" title="Lotus Sutra">Lotus Sutra</a> lists the <a href="/wiki/Paramita" title="Paramita" class="mw-redirect">Six Perfections</a> (<i>paramita</i>) which echoes the threefold training with the inclusion of virtue (<i><a href="/wiki/Sila" title="Sila">śīla</a></i>), concentration (<i><a href="/wiki/Dhyana" title="Dhyana" class="mw-redirect">dhyāna</a></i>) and wisdom (<i><a href="/wiki/Prajna" title="Prajna" class="mw-redirect">prajñā</a></i>).</li>
